MORK Notes : We made a planning video that suggests different frames
and main subjects and then spits out potential scenes from the video analysis. The goal
is to use the analysis to decide what the best shots are and how to provide that detail to the app
or claude when the video is being edited.

--- Session Summary (2026-04-19) ---

Built tools/plan_video.py — a new standalone planning tool that runs the existing subject-tracking
pipeline (MediaPipe face + YOLOv8 body fallback, same as cut_clips) against a full raw video and
outputs three files to .tmp/planning/{video_stem}/:

  {stem}_debug_planning.mp4   — full-res debug video with detection boxes, crop window edges,
                                 segment labels (top-left), and white flash at each segment boundary.
                                 Supports --audio flag to mux the original audio track in.

  {stem}_scenes_planning.csv  — scene breakdown, one row per segment, ready to fill in Google Sheets.
  {stem}_scenes_planning.json — same data in JSON for programmatic use.

Segmentation is adaptive — the tool splits on two triggers:
  mode_change : tracker switches between face-detection and body-detection
  crop_jump   : crop window position jumps > --jump-threshold pixels in one frame (default 150)
A --min-segment guard (default 2.0s) prevents noise from creating tiny segments.

Each scene row includes auto-computed fields (start/end times, dominant mode, detection rate,
avg crop position, crop stability) plus four blank user-fillable columns: label, subject_focus,
description, pan_plan. The intent is to watch the debug video, fill those in, and use the result
as a shot list when running cut_clips.

Also wrote PLAN_VIDEO_README.md in the project root — a full field reference explaining every
column, what the values mean, how to read the debug video, and the end-to-end workflow.

Tested against Magic_V2B_Yellow_Charlie — produced 5 segments, all mode_change triggers,
detection rate 0.988–1.0 across all segments.
